#MEM id=examples source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Finance/felix/skills/executive-operations/saas-revenue-growth-metrics/examples/warning-signs.md
M|examples|**Company:** MarketingFlow (SMB mkt automation SaaS)
M|examples|**Stage:** Early growth, post-Seed
M|examples|**Customer Base:** 2,000 accounts, 10,000 users
M|examples|**Period:** Monthly snapshot
M|examples|```
M|examples|Starting MRR: $500,000
M|examples|+ New MRR: $100,000 (200 new accounts)
M|examples|+ Expansion MRR: $5,000 (minimal upsells)
M|examples|- Churned MRR: $50,000 (120 accounts churned)
M|examples|- Contraction MRR: $10,000 (40 accounts downgraded)
M|examples|Ending MRR: $545,000
M|examples|MRR Growth Rate: 9% MoM (but driven entirely by new customer acquisition)
M|examples|ARR: $6.5M
M|examples|```
M|examples|```
M|examples|ARPA = $545,000 / 2,000 accounts = $272/month
M|examples|ARPU = $545,000 / 10,000 users = $54.50/month
M|examples|Average seats per account = 5 users
M|examples|```
M|examples|```
M|examples|New MRR: $100K (20% of base — very high)
M|examples|Expansion MRR: $5K (1% of base — very low)
M|examples|Churned MRR: $50K (10% of base — crisis level)
M|examples|Contraction MRR: $10K (2% of base — concerning)
M|examples|```
M|examples|```
M|examples|Logo Churn: 120 / 2,000 = 6% monthly (~50% annual)
M|examples|Revenue Churn: $50K / $500K = 10% monthly (~69% annual)
M|examples|```
M|examples|**Analysis:** Revenue churn > logo churn = losing bigger customers. Crisis signal.
M|examples|```
M|examples|Starting ARR: $6M
M|examples|Expansion: $60K (annual)
M|examples|Churned: $600K (annual)
M|examples|Contraction: $120K (annual)
M|examples|Ending ARR: $5.34M
M|examples|NRR = $5.34M / $6M = 89%
M|examples|```
M|examples|**Analysis:** NRR <100% = contracting base. Losing revenue from existing customers faster than expanding them.
M|examples|```
M|examples|Gains = $100K + $5K = $105K
M|examples|Losses = $50K + $10K = $60K
M|examples|Quick Ratio = $105K / $60K = 1.75
M|examples|```
M|examples|**Analysis:** Quick Ratio <2 = leaky bucket. Barely outpacing losses.
M|examples|| Cohort | Month 3 Retention | Month 6 Retention | Month 12 Retention |
M|examples||--------|-------------------|-------------------|---------------------|
M|examples|| 12 months ago | 82% | 75% | 68% |
M|examples|| 6 months ago | 75% | 65% | TBD |
M|examples|| Current | 68% (on track) | TBD | TBD |
M|examples|**Analysis:** Newer cohorts churning FASTER than older cohorts. Product-market fit is degrading.
M|examples|**Unsustainable churn:**
M|examples|- 6% monthly logo churn = ~50% annual (crisis level)
M|examples|- 10% monthly revenue churn = ~69% annual (existential threat)
M|examples|- Revenue churn > logo churn = losing high-value customers
M|examples|- Churn rate increasing (was 4% six months ago)
M|examples|**Cohort degradation:**
M|examples|- Newer customers churn faster than older customers
M|examples|- Month 6 retention: 75% → 65% → on track for 58%
M|examples|- This signals product-market fit is getting WORSE, not better
M|examples|**No expansion engine:**
M|examples|- Expansion revenue only 1% of MRR (should be 10-30%)
M|examples|- NRR at 89% (contracting, not expanding)
M|examples|- Only 5% of customers have ever expanded
M|examples|**Leaky bucket:**
M|examples|- Quick Ratio 1.75 (barely exceeding losses)
M|examples|- Losing $60K/month, only gaining $105K/month
M|examples|- Running on a treadmill: need 200 new customers/month just to stay flat
M|examples|**Revenue dependency:**
M|examples|- 90% of growth from new customer acquisition
M|examples|- If acquisition slows, revenue will shrink immediately
M|examples|- Retention is broken—scaling will just accelerate the problem
M|examples|**Why is churn increasing?**
M|examples|- Product quality degrading?
M|examples|- Wrong customer segment (poor fit)?
M|examples|- Onboarding failures?
M|examples|- Competitive pressure?
M|examples|- Pricing too high for value delivered?
M|examples|**Why are newer cohorts worse?**
M|examples|- Customer acquisition quality degrading?
M|examples|- Product changes breaking key use cases?
M|examples|- Support quality declining as company scales?
M|examples|**Why no expansion?**
M|examples|- No upsell paths in packaging?
M|examples|- Customers not reaching "aha moment" where they'd expand?
M|examples|- Product doesn't grow with customer needs?
M|examples|Do NOT increase mkt spend until retention is fixed. Scaling a leaky bucket just burns cash faster.
M|examples|**Why:** At current churn rates, every dollar spent acquiring customers leaks out within 12 months. Fix the bucket first.
M|examples|**Investigate churn:**
M|examples|1. Run churn interviews with 20-30 churned customers
M|examples|2. Segment churn by cohort, use case, customer size
M|examples|3. Identify top 3 churn reasons
M|examples|**Quick wins:**
M|examples|1. Improve onboarding (70% of churn happens in first 60 days)
M|examples|2. Proactive support for at-risk accounts (identify usage drop-offs)
M|examples|3. Re-engage dormant accounts before they churn
M|examples|**Goal:** Reduce logo churn from 6% to 4% within 8 weeks, target 3% within 16 weeks.
M|examples|**Create upsell paths:**
M|examples|1. Introduce premium tier (advanced features)
M|examples|2. Usage-based add-ons (additional seats, integrations)
M|examples|3. Cross-sell complementary features
M|examples|**Identify expansion candidates:**
M|examples|1. Which customers use product heavily? (Target for upsell)
M|examples|2. Which customers hit usage limits? (Offer expansion)
M|examples|**Goal:** Increase expansion MRR from 1% to 5% of base within 12 weeks.
M|examples|**Track cohorts rigorously:**
M|examples|1. Weekly cohort retention dashboards
M|examples|2. Compare new cohorts to baseline (75% at Month 6)
M|examples|3. Don't scale until new cohorts retain BETTER than old cohorts
M|examples|**Product improvements:**
M|examples|1. Fix onboarding (time-to-value)
M|examples|2. Improve core use cases (reduce churn reasons)
M|examples|3. Add sticky features (integrations, data accumulation)
M|examples|**Goal:** Reverse cohort degradation trend within 16 weeks. New cohorts should retain at 75%+ by Month 6.
M|examples|Do NOT scale acquisition until:
M|examples|- [ ] Logo churn <4% monthly (ideally <3%)
M|examples|- [ ] Revenue churn <5% monthly
M|examples|- [ ] NRR >100% (expansion exceeds churn)
M|examples|- [ ] Quick Ratio >2.5 (ideally >4)
M|examples|- [ ] New cohorts retain same or better than old cohorts
M|examples|- [ ] Expansion MRR >5% of total MRR
M|examples|**Timeline:** 12-16 weeks to fix. Then reassess scaling.
M|examples|**Current state (bad):**
M|examples|- Need 200 new customers/month just to offset churn
M|examples|- Net growth: only 80 customers/month after churn
M|examples|- 90% of acquisition spend wasted on replacing churned customers
M|examples|**If churn fixed to 3% (good):**
M|examples|- Need 60 new customers/month to offset churn
M|examples|- Net growth: 140 customers/month (75% more efficient)
M|examples|- Acquisition budget goes 3x further
M|examples|**If NRR fixed to 110% (great):**
M|examples|- Existing base grows 10%/year without new customers
M|examples|- All new acquisition is net growth
M|examples|- Can afford higher CAC because LTV increases 2-3x
M|examples|**Bottom line:** Fixing retention is worth 6-12 months of paused growth. Don't skip this.